            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Gas Stoves:</h3>
              <p>
                Gas stoves are a popular choice in many commercial kitchens due to their quick heating and precise temperature control. However, they come with their own set of repair needs. Common issues include malfunctioning burners, gas leaks, and problems with the ignition system. Repairing a gas stove often involves checking the gas lines for leaks, cleaning or replacing clogged burners, and fixing or replacing the ignition switch. Costs for these repairs can vary, but typically range from <b>$150 to $400</b>, depending on the severity of the issue. Regular maintenance, such as cleaning burners and checking gas connections, can help prevent many of these problems and ensure the stove operates efficiently.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Electric Stoves:</h3>
              <p>
                Electric stoves are known for their even heating and ease of use, making them another popular option in commercial settings. Common issues with electric stoves include faulty heating elements, broken thermostats, and issues with the stove’s wiring. Repairs might involve replacing a heating element, fixing wiring issues, or recalibrating the thermostat. These repairs generally cost between <b>$100 and $300</b>. Regular maintenance for electric stoves includes checking the heating elements for wear and ensuring that the electrical connections are secure. By addressing minor issues early on, businesses can avoid more costly repairs and prolong the life of their electric stoves.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Induction Stoves:</h3>
              <p>
                Induction stoves are highly efficient and provide rapid heating by using electromagnetic fields to directly heat cookware. However, they require specialized repairs when issues arise. Common problems include malfunctioning induction coils, faulty control panels, and issues with the stove's sensors. Repairing an induction stove can be more complex and may require specialized knowledge, often leading to higher repair costs ranging from <b>$200 to $500</b>. Regular maintenance, such as cleaning the cooktop surface and ensuring that the cookware used is compatible with induction cooking, can help prevent many common issues and keep the stove in optimal working condition.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Dual Fuel Stoves:</h3>
              <p>
                Dual fuel stoves combine the best of both gas and electric stoves, offering a gas cooktop with an electric oven. While they provide versatility and precision, they also come with a unique set of repair needs. Issues can arise in both the gas and electric components, including problems with gas burners, electric heating elements, and electronic control systems. Repairing a dual fuel stove can be more involved and costly, with prices typically ranging from <b>$250 to $600</b>, depending on the nature of the problem. Regular maintenance should include checking both gas and electric components, cleaning burners, and ensuring that the control systems are functioning correctly. This holistic approach to maintenance can help prevent costly breakdowns and extend the life of the stove.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Convection Stoves:</h3>
              <p>
                Convection stoves are prized for their ability to cook food evenly and quickly, thanks to a built-in fan that circulates hot air. Common repair needs for convection stoves include issues with the convection fan, heating elements, and temperature sensors. Repairs might involve replacing a malfunctioning fan motor, fixing the heating elements, or recalibrating the temperature sensors. These repairs can range from <b>$150 to $400</b>. Regular maintenance for convection stoves includes cleaning the fan and oven interior and checking the functionality of the heating elements and sensors. Keeping these components in good working order can prevent uneven cooking and other issues, ensuring the stove performs at its best.
              </p>
            </div>

