             <ul>
              <li>
                <b>Burners: </b>
                <p>Burners are the heart of any commercial stove, responsible for delivering the heat necessary for cooking. They come in various types, including open burners, griddle burners, and broilers, each designed for specific cooking needs. High-quality burners ensure efficient fuel consumption and consistent heat distribution, which is crucial for maintaining food quality and preparation times in a busy kitchen. Replacement burners must be compatible with the stove model and meet safety standards to prevent hazards such as gas leaks or uneven heating.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Knobs and Valves: </b>
                <p>Knobs and valves are essential for controlling the burners on a commercial stove. They allow chefs to adjust the flame intensity with precision, which is vital for cooking delicate dishes or maintaining a consistent temperature. Over time, these components can wear out or break, making it difficult to operate the stove efficiently. Replacing worn-out knobs and valves with durable, high-quality parts ensures smooth operation and helps prevent accidents caused by malfunctioning controls.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Igniters and Pilots: </b>
                <p>Igniters and pilot assemblies are crucial for the initial ignition of the stove burners. Igniters provide the spark needed to light the burners, while pilot assemblies maintain a small, continuous flame that can ignite the burners quickly when needed. Faulty igniters or pilot lights can lead to delays in cooking and pose safety risks. It is essential to replace these parts promptly with reliable, manufacturer-approved components to ensure the stove operates safely and efficiently.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Thermostats: </b>
                <p>Thermostats regulate the temperature within ovens and griddles, ensuring that food is cooked evenly and to the desired level. In a commercial kitchen, precise temperature control is vital for food safety and quality. A malfunctioning thermostat can lead to undercooked or overcooked dishes, wasting time and ingredients. Replacing defective thermostats with accurate, durable models helps maintain consistent cooking temperatures and enhances the overall efficiency of the kitchen.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Grates and Racks: </b>
                <p>Grates and racks provide the surface on which pots, pans, and food items sit during cooking. They must withstand high temperatures and heavy use without warping or breaking. Over time, these components can become coated with grease, food particles, or suffer from wear and tear. Replacing worn or damaged grates and racks ensures proper heat distribution and supports the weight of cookware, contributing to safer and more efficient kitchen operations.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Oven Door Seals: </b>
                <p>Oven door seals, or gaskets, are essential for maintaining the internal temperature of the oven by preventing heat from escaping. A well-sealed oven ensures that food cooks evenly and energy is not wasted. Over time, seals can become brittle or damaged, leading to heat loss and increased cooking times. Replacing old or faulty seals with high-quality, heat-resistant materials helps maintain the oven’s efficiency and reduces energy consumption.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Control Panels and Displays: </b>
                <p>Control panels and displays provide the interface for setting temperatures, timers, and other functions on a commercial stove. These components must be intuitive and durable to withstand the rigors of a busy kitchen environment. A malfunctioning control panel can disrupt kitchen operations and lead to cooking errors. Upgrading to a new, reliable control panel ensures that kitchen staff can easily and accurately operate the stove, enhancing overall productivity and safety.</p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <b>Drip Pans and Trays: </b>
                <p>Drip pans and trays catch spills and drips from cooking, helping to keep the stove clean and reducing the risk of fires. They must be easy to remove and clean to maintain hygiene standards in a commercial kitchen. Over time, drip pans and trays can become corroded or damaged, making them less effective. Replacing these components regularly ensures that the stove remains clean and safe to use, and helps prolong the life of the appliance.</p>
              </li>
